{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"477aba1c-e470-4e9a-83e3-3a735e8758ca","content":"## What happened\n\n**Apple's Security.framework on macOS does not implement DSA.** In .NET 10, the runtime still shipped a managed/OpenSSL-based fallback for DSA on macOS. In .NET 11, that fallback was removed as part of the ongoing deprecation of legacy crypto algorithms, so `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.\n\nLinux (OpenSSL) and Windows (CNG) continue to support DSA natively, which is why those platforms are unaffected.\n\n## How to fix it\n\n**Short-term — use OpenSSL explicitly on macOS:**\n\nInstall OpenSSL (e.g., `brew install openssl`) and use `DSAOpenSsl` conditionally:\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Runtime.InteropServices;\nusing System.Security.Cryptography;\n\nDSA CreateDsa()\n{\n    if (RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.OSX))\n    {\n        // Requires OpenSSL installed via Homebrew or similar\n        return new DSAOpenSsl();\n    }\n    return DSA.Create();\n}\n```\n\nTo import an existing key on macOS, load it through the OpenSSL-backed type:\n\n```csharp\nvar dsa = new DSAOpenSsl();\ndsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(publicKeyBytes, out _);\nbool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);\n```\n\n**Long-term — migrate away from DSA entirely.** DSA is a legacy algorithm with limited key/hash sizes. Move to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** (via `ECDsa.Create()` or the `EdDSA` APIs in newer .NET), which are supported natively on all three platforms. Keep DSA verification only as a backward-compatibility path for old signatures that can't be re-signed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c484011f-5225-418c-9ebc-bb9a9fa32ca9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue related to DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) and `DSA.Create()` failing on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET platform changes, not a codebase task.\n\nLet me think about what I know:\n\nIn .NET, the `DSA.Create()` method creates a platform-specific implementation of DSA. On different platforms:\n- **Windows**: Uses CNG (Cryptography Next Generation) - `DSACng`\n- **Linux**: Uses OpenSSL - `DSAOpenSsl`\n\n\n- **macOS**: Apple deprecated DSA support in their security frameworks, so .NET no longer provides a working implementation on that platform\n\nThe core issue is that Apple removed DSA from CommonCrypto/Security framework, and .NET 9+ stopped trying to work around this limitation. Earlier versions might have had fallbacks or used deprecated APIs, but newer .NET releases align with the OS's cryptographic support.\n\nOn macOS specifically, `DSA.Create()` historically relied on OpenSSL or Apple's deprecated security APIs. Apple has been phasing out these older cryptographic standards in favor of modern alternatives, which is why the implementation broke in recent .NET versions. Looking back at the actual timeline, DSA support on macOS in .NET has been problematic since the early .NET Core days—`DSA.Create()` was throwing `PlatformNotSupportedException` because Apple's security frameworks never had native DSA support, and the managed fallback implementation that .NET relied on is being phased out.\n\nSo the real issue here is that in .NET 11, that software fallback was completely removed, leaving no way to use DSA on macOS at all. The fix would involve either switching to a different algorithm or using a third-party cryptography library that still supports DSA. DSAOpenSsl might not be directly available on macOS since .NET typically relies on Apple's security framework rather than OpenSSL by default, though OpenSSL can be installed and used if needed.\n\nThe real issue is that Apple's native security frameworks don't support DSA, and .NET 11 removed the fallback mechanism that previously handled this on macOS. So `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. If you need DSA support, you'd have to explicitly use `DSAOpenSsl` with OpenSSL installed, though that's not the standard path on macOS. Apple's crypto frameworks don't support DSA, and .NET has been progressively removing fallback implementations for platform-unsupported algorithms—DSA specifically throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS in .NET Core and later versions. The practical solution is either to explicitly use OpenSSL or migrate to a modern algorithm like ECDSA or Ed25519.","outputTokens":2507,"requestId":"6C2C:2F74C2:EBAD1E:1134933:69FE931C"},"id":"4b87240f-c34e-4415-abe8-4b5795ad814b","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:52:18.375Z","parentId":"f2f68453-0885-45dc-86f5-333f58517655"}
